# Evidence For

## Primate Evidence

<Primate CR Survival> #pro

(1) [Wisconsin Survival]: Mattison et al. 2017 reconciled the Wisconsin
    and NIA rhesus monkey CR studies in a joint reanalysis. #observation
    > "these data confirm that health benefits of CR are conserved in monkeys and suggest that CR mechanisms are likely translatable to human health"
    [Mattison et al. 2017, Nature Communications](https://doi.org/10.1038/ncomms14063)
    {credence: 0.82, reason: "joint reanalysis by both study teams, published in Nature Comms, 783 citations"}
(2) [Wisconsin Mortality]: Colman et al. 2014 showed CR significantly
    reduced age-related and all-cause mortality in rhesus monkeys
    on ~30% restriction since young adulthood. #observation
    > "CR significantly improves age-related and all-cause survival in monkeys on a long-term ~30% restricted diet since young adulthood"
    [Colman et al. 2014, Nature Communications](https://doi.org/10.1038/ncomms4557)
    {credence: 0.80, reason: "671 citations, long-term study, but single cohort"}
(3) [Primate Translatable]: If CR extends lifespan in our closest
    evolutionary relatives, the mechanism is likely conserved in
    humans. #assumption
    {credence: 0.55, reason: "plausible but humans differ in metabolism, diet, environment; 30-year monkey lifespan vs 80-year human lifespan makes direct extrapolation uncertain"}
--
Primate survival benefits suggest CR mechanisms translate to humans {uses: [1, 2, 3]}
--
(4) [Primate Evidence Supports]: CR extends survival in primates,
    suggesting conserved longevity mechanisms relevant to humans.
    {inference: 0.65, reason: "strong primate evidence but translating magnitude to humans requires assumptions"}
  +> [CR Extends Human Lifespan]

## Human Biomarker Evidence

<CALERIE Slows Aging> #pro

(1) [DunedinPACE Result]: Waziry et al. 2023 found that 2 years of CR
    slowed the pace of biological aging as measured by DunedinPACE in
    the CALERIE RCT (n=220 healthy adults). #observation
    > "CALERIE intervention slowed the pace of aging, as measured by the DunedinPACE DNAm algorithm"
    [Waziry et al. 2023, Nature Aging](https://doi.org/10.1038/s43587-022-00357-y)
    {credence: 0.88, reason: "RCT, 205 citations, published in Nature Aging, rigorous methodology"}
(2) [Small Effect]: The same study found the treatment effect was a
    2-3% reduction in pace of aging (Cohen's d ~0.25). #observation
    > "Treatment effect sizes were small. Nevertheless, modest slowing of the pace of aging can have profound effects on population health"
    [Waziry et al. 2023, Nature Aging](https://doi.org/10.1038/s43587-022-00357-y)
    {credence: 0.88, reason: "same RCT, directly reported effect size"}
(3) [Biomarker To Lifespan]: Slowing the pace of biological aging as
    measured by DNAm proxies translates to actual lifespan extension. #assumption
    {credence: 0.45, reason: "DunedinPACE predicts mortality in observational data, but no interventional proof that changing it changes lifespan"}
--
An RCT shows CR slows a validated aging biomarker, but translation to lifespan is unproven {uses: [1, 2, 3]}
--
(4) [Biomarker Supports CR]: CR slows biological aging in humans per
    RCT evidence, but the magnitude is small and the lifespan link
    is indirect.
    {inference: 0.50, reason: "surrogate endpoint, not hard mortality data; effect size is modest"}
  +> [CR Extends Human Lifespan]

