# Evidence Against

## No Direct Evidence

<No Direct Human Evidence> #con

(1) [No Mortality RCT]: No randomized controlled trial has measured
    the effect of CR on human mortality or lifespan as a primary
    endpoint. #assumption
    {credence: 0.95, reason: "factual: no such trial exists or is feasible given human lifespan"}
(2) [Surrogate Gap]: The CALERIE trial used biomarkers, not mortality,
    and its authors note this limitation explicitly. #observation
    > "a conclusive test of the geroscience hypothesis will require trials with long-term follow-up to establish effects of intervention on primary healthy-aging endpoints, including incidence of chronic disease and mortality"
    [Waziry et al. 2023, Nature Aging](https://doi.org/10.1038/s43587-022-00357-y)
    {credence: 0.90, reason: "authors themselves acknowledge this gap"}
--
Without mortality data, the core claim remains unproven in humans {uses: [1, 2]}
--
(3) [No Hard Evidence]: The claim that CR extends human lifespan
    lacks direct experimental support.
    {inference: 0.85, reason: "absence of evidence is strong when the right experiment has never been done"}
  -> [CR Extends Human Lifespan]

## Contradictory Primate Results

<Primate Studies Contradictory> #con

(1) [NIA No Survival]: Mattison et al. 2012 reported the NIA primate
    study found no significant survival benefit of CR. #observation
    > "Impact of caloric restriction on health and survival in rhesus monkeys from the NIA study"
    [Mattison et al. 2012, Nature](https://doi.org/10.1038/nature11432)
    {credence: 0.80, reason: "published in Nature, well-designed, but later reconciliation paper explains some discrepancies"}
(2) [Diet Differences]: The 2017 reconciliation attributed differences
    partly to diet composition and onset age, meaning CR effects are
    sensitive to implementation details. #observation
    > "We describe differences in study design that could contribute to differences in outcomes, and we report species specificity in the impact of CR in terms of optimal onset and diet"
    [Mattison et al. 2017, Nature Communications](https://doi.org/10.1038/ncomms14063)
    {credence: 0.82, reason: "same reconciliation paper; acknowledged by both research groups"}
--
Primate evidence is weaker than it appears because results depend on protocol details {uses: [1, 2]}
--
(3) [Primate Fragile]: The primate survival benefit is sensitive to
    diet composition and onset timing, weakening its generalizability.
    {inference: 0.55, reason: "reconciliation explains some discrepancy but also shows effect is fragile"}
  -> [CR Extends Human Lifespan]

## Adverse Effects

<Muscle And Bone Loss> #con

(1) [Lean Mass Loss]: Caloric restriction in humans causes loss of lean
    body mass, typically ~25-30% of total weight lost is muscle. #observation
    > "Caloric restriction alone improves physical function and quality of life in older adults with obesity but is associated with loss of lean mass and increases fracture risk"
    [Jiang & Villareal 2019, Current Opinion in Clinical Nutrition](https://doi.org/10.1097/MCO.0000000000000520)
    {credence: 0.80, reason: "review of clinical evidence, consistent across multiple studies"}
(2) [Sarcopenia Risk]: In older adults, muscle loss from CR could
    accelerate sarcopenia, increasing fall risk and mortality. #assumption
    {credence: 0.60, reason: "clinically plausible, especially relevant for the older population most interested in longevity interventions"}
--
CR side effects could offset lifespan gains, especially in older adults {uses: [1, 2]}
--
(3) [Adverse Effects Offset]: Muscle and bone loss from CR may
    partially offset any longevity benefit, particularly in elderly
    populations.
    {inference: 0.45, reason: "real concern but potentially mitigable with exercise and protein; CALERIE participants were not old"}
  -> [CR Extends Human Lifespan]

## Adherence Undercut

<Adherence Undercut> #con

(1) [Poor Adherence]: In CALERIE, participants prescribed 25% CR
    actually achieved only ~12% on average. #observation
    > "the %CR achieved by participants in the treatment group varied, with most participants achieving doses below the prescribed 25% (mean = 11.9, s.e.m. = 0.7%)"
    [Waziry et al. 2023, Nature Aging](https://doi.org/10.1038/s43587-022-00357-y)
    {credence: 0.90, reason: "directly reported from the RCT"}
----
(2) [Adherence Limits Translation]: Even if CR works in principle,
    sustained adherence at effective doses may be impractical for
    most humans.
    {inference: 0.70, reason: "practical concern that limits real-world benefit even if mechanism is real"}
  _> <CALERIE Slows Aging>

